{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"coaching":[{"coaching":"Test the riskiest assumption behind git object availability for history recovery first.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f4a5627db39d908dc","ff0257b18b4099f49","f4499a8fb0372bf30","fb0216183d19fb5b9"],"move_id":"4","move_name":"riskiest-assumption test","subject":"git object availability for history recovery"},{"coaching":"Pin down post_claim_edit_class assignment rules for reopened tickets with a concrete worked example.","decision":"block","finding_refs":["f03903d730611dc7c","f5b60e7ce1471757c"],"move_id":"6","move_name":"specification by example","subject":"post_claim_edit_class assignment rules for reopened tickets"},{"coaching":"State the concrete attestation evidence the [operator-attested] ticket ID existence and defect-class assignments will require (a change id / vote outcome / timestamp), recorded on the ticket.","decision":"block","finding_refs":["fae3d31323d7f7a12","fce53c271be757af8"],"move_id":"14","move_name":"state attestation evidence","subject":"ticket ID existence and defect-class assignments"},{"coaching":"Plan how pre-flight probe failure-path AC coverage will be verified in-session — restate any deferred or unobservable success target as an observable proxy.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["faeb4424bbdc36ac6","fd2c3fd12bc39c968","fbbe04115d12cf59f","ffa90c0998fba5072"],"move_id":"9","move_name":"plan the verification","subject":"pre-flight probe failure-path AC coverage"},{"coaching":"Research prior art / OSS for dropped-finding data source in REVIEW_RESULT sidecars before building it custom.","decision":"block","finding_refs":["f144544a66d90ceee","f4a5627db39d908dc"],"move_id":"2","move_name":"prior-art research","subject":"dropped-finding data source in REVIEW_RESULT sidecars"},{"coaching":"Pin down had_persisted_review field computation method with a concrete worked example.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f2df6a10fbfb039aa","f08553e2341f69054"],"move_id":"6","move_name":"specification by example","subject":"had_persisted_review field computation method"},{"coaching":"Pin down adjudication corpus creation script interface with a concrete worked example.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["fac4b1f9f0b0e2e6b"],"move_id":"6","move_name":"specification by example","subject":"adjudication corpus creation script interface"},{"coaching":"Pin down rubric content and quality requirements with a concrete worked example.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f159fc6bf72cfea57","fac228730921f4dbe","fd2f717e7283c0bbd"],"move_id":"6","move_name":"specification by example","subject":"rubric content and quality requirements"},{"coaching":"Pin down blind-labeling enforcement protocol for Rater B with a concrete worked example.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f01efc6c7f90f94fc"],"move_id":"6","move_name":"specification by example","subject":"blind-labeling enforcement protocol for Rater B"},{"coaching":"Plan how rubric file commitment verification in AC will be verified in-session — restate any deferred or unobservable success target as an observable proxy.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f4a95e06dab793b45"],"move_id":"9","move_name":"plan the verification","subject":"rubric file commitment verification in AC"},{"coaching":"Run a quick pre-mortem on LLM rater error handling and partial-state recovery: how could this plan fail?","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f4fe137c190edcc1d"],"move_id":"3","move_name":"pre-mortem","subject":"LLM rater error handling and partial-state recovery"},{"coaching":"Weigh at least one structural alternative for kappa.py reuse of existing cohens_kappa implementation.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["fdb880e51d6b226dd"],"move_id":"5","move_name":"weigh alternatives","subject":"kappa.py reuse of existing cohens_kappa implementation"},{"coaching":"State the concrete attestation evidence the [operator-attested] epic pastoral-aquatic-viper reference provenance will require (a change id / vote outcome / timestamp), recorded on the ticket.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f4606dd4b09665b7d"],"move_id":"14","move_name":"state attestation evidence","subject":"epic pastoral-aquatic-viper reference provenance"},{"coaching":"Plan how AC3 concrete jq/python proving command will be verified in-session — restate any deferred or unobservable success target as an observable proxy.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["ffa90c0998fba5072","f607dd457c67f9209"],"move_id":"9","move_name":"plan the verification","subject":"AC3 concrete jq/python proving command"}],"coverage":{"counts":{"advisory_overflow":6,"advisory_surfaced":15,"blocking":5,"dropped":14,"indeterminate":0},"det":{"P1":{"ac_items":4,"blocking":false,"clarity_score":7,"name":"readiness-shape","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P2":{"blocking":false,"name":"resolution","probed":11,"ran":true,"references":11,"resolved":0,"status":"pass","unresolved_or_abstained":11},"P3":{"blocking":false,"name":"package-existence","packages":0,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P4":{"ac_items":4,"blocking":false,"desc_chars":8901,"file_impact":1,"name":"oversize","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P5":{"blocking":false,"children":0,"name":"task-dag","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P6":{"ac_items":4,"blocking":false,"name":"ac-quality","ran":true,"status":"fail","verify_commands_linted":91,"verify_lint_abstained":90},"P7":{"blocking":false,"destructive_hits":[],"name":"destructive-sniff","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P8":{"blocking":false,"budget_tokens":868000,"name":"reviewability","plan_tokens":2247,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P9":{"applicable":true,"blocking":false,"file_impact":1,"name":"file-impact-coverage","ran":true,"status":"pass"}},"floored_criteria":["A1","E1","E2","E4","G1G2"],"floored_finding_ids":["f4a5627db39d908dc","fb0216183d19fb5b9","f08553e2341f69054","fdb880e51d6b226dd","f4606dd4b09665b7d"],"llm_ran":true,"metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":216.6,"llm_calls":30,"llm_ms":558759.3,"total_ms":559121.1,"verify_requests":23},"narrowed":true,"remediation":{"baseline":"sidecar","eligible":true,"reasons":{"code_unchanged":true,"plan_changed":true,"registry_unchanged":true,"sidecar_baseline":true,"within_window":true}},"routing":{"agent_tier":["A1","E4","G1G2","G6","G7","T1","T10","T11","T13","T14","T3","T5c","T8","removal-rationale"],"single_turn":["COH","E1","E2","E3","E5","E6","F1","F4","G5","T2","T4","T5b","T5d","T5e","T6","T7","T9","hedge"]}},"findings":[{"block_threshold":0.75,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a locatable pointer to the §5 report (a committed file path or a stable URL) and confirm the specific published figures (16/505, 15/16, 3 MISSED, etc.) appear there, so the --verify-s5 re-verification table has a verifiable baseline.","cohort":["E4"],"criteria":["E4"],"decision":"block","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: 'report §5 §5.2 … report commit 143d5074e'","Search for '143d5074e' returns no matches in the repo","Search for '16/505' returns only cached plan-review outputs, not a source report document","Search for 'plan-review-gate-dogfood-baseline.md' in docs/experiments finds the file but it contains no §5 figures matching those in the plan","ABSENCE: no report document containing '16/505', 'dc58', '5886', 'c8cc', 'f5df', '115b', '8c4f', '3006' is findable in the repo"],"finding":"The plan's foundational §5 headline figures (16/505 post-claim edits, 15/16 substantive, 8 persisted-review subset, 3 MISSED / dc58, db7b, 5886 / asserted-capability defect class, 4 CAUGHT-BUT-IGNORED, 1 UNKNOWABLE) are stated as facts whose source is 'report §5' and 'report commit 143d5074e', but neither document is locatable in the repo. No file at any path contains these specific figures or the cited commit hash, so the assertions are unverifiable and the mining script's --verify-s5 mode has no independent ground-truth baseline to validate against.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fce53c271be757af8","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What §2 (re-verify §5 headline claims); AC#2; Scope (provenance: 'report commit 143d5074e')","norm_id":"n2f3e5b59371e20ec","priority":1.0,"reason":"high-priority+criterion-opted-in","scenarios":["The mining script's --verify-s5 mode produces derived figures (e.g. 14/503) with no way to determine whether to emit AGREES or CORRECTED-TO because the §5 published baseline is not locatable.","An executor implementing the re-verification table cannot populate the 'published figure' column without the source report."],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"Commit the report as a markdown file under docs/experiments/ (e.g. docs/experiments/plan-review-outcome-report.md) containing the §5 figures, or add a `REPORT_FIGURES` dict literal to mine_outcome_corpus.py encoding each published value so they are version-controlled and the diff is machine-checkable.","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"high","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.75,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Verify that ticket IDs dc58, 5886, c8cc, f5df, 115b, 8c4f, and 3006 are accessible via `rebar show` in this store, and clarify that the §5 'db7b' reference is a different ticket from the sidecar story `db7b`; add a disambiguation note in the plan or use full IDs.","cohort":["E4"],"criteria":["E4"],"decision":"block","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: 'the 3 MISSED cases and that they share the asserted-capability defect class (§5: dc58, db7b, 5886), the 4 CAUGHT-BUT-IGNORED (c8cc, f5df, 115b, 8c4f), and the 1 UNKNOWABLE (3006)'","Search for 'dc58' returns only plan-review cache entries, not actual ticket data","Search for 'c8cc', '5886', 'f5df', '115b', '8c4f', '3006' returns no matches in the repo","Search for 'db7b' returns matches but these refer to the REVIEW_RESULT sidecar story (src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py), not a §5 missed-review case"],"finding":"The plan asserts that specific ticket IDs dc58, 5886, c8cc, f5df, 115b, 8c4f, and 3006 exist in the store and hold the defect-class and disposition assignments described (3 MISSED / asserted-capability, 4 CAUGHT-BUT-IGNORED, 1 UNKNOWABLE). None of these IDs are findable anywhere in the repo (code, docs, or test fixtures), so the claim that dc58/db7b/5886 share the 'asserted-capability defect class' is an unverifiable assertion that drives a concrete AC verification step.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fae3d31323d7f7a12","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What §2 (re-verify §5 headline claims); AC#2 ('the 3-MISSED asserted-capability defect class on dc58/db7b/5886')","norm_id":"na08ca30afca4de6f","priority":1.0,"reason":"high-priority+criterion-opted-in","scenarios":["The executor runs --verify-s5 and attempts to confirm dc58/db7b/5886 are 'asserted-capability' defect class, but rebar show dc58 fails (ticket not found) or returns a ticket whose content doesn't match the claimed defect class.","'db7b' resolves to the sidecar retention story and its defect class is plainly not 'asserted-capability', causing the verification step to silently produce wrong results."],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"high","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify the concrete data source and extraction method for the ~100 `source=dropped` findings in Step 3 (e.g., PASS-verdict criterion rows from REVIEW_RESULT sidecar payloads, or a re-sampling run of the gate with criterion-level PASS logging), so AC#3's ≥90 dropped floor is achievable and the TP/FP semantics are consistent.","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"block","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan Step 3: 'stratified sample of plan-review findings drawn from the persisted REVIEW_RESULT sidecars: target ~300 surfaced (block + advisory) and ~100 dropped findings'","Plan Step 3 schema: 'source ∈ {surfaced, dropped}, decision ∈ {block, advisory, dropped}'","REVIEW_RESULT sidecar stores surfaced findings only; PASS-verdict criteria produce no finding text in the sidecar (confirmed by src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py structure)","No mechanism in the Scope or Steps names a secondary source for dropped/PASS-verdict findings"],"finding":"The ~100 `source=dropped` finding rows required by AC#3 have no named data source in the plan. REVIEW_RESULT sidecars store only surfaced findings (non-empty verdict rows); a criterion that produced no finding emits only a PASS verdict with no finding text, which cannot be extracted and labeled as a 'dropped' finding without re-running the gate or consulting an alternative log. The plan never specifies how to obtain the 'dropped' population, making Step 3's data-flow incomplete and the AC#3 floor (≥90 dropped) unachievable as written.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f144544a66d90ceee","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 3 (Build the finding-adjudication corpus); AC#3","norm_id":"ndc629ad0a077773f","priority":1.0,"reason":"high-priority+criterion-opted-in","scenarios":["Implementer reads REVIEW_RESULT sidecars and finds only surfaced rows; cannot produce 90 dropped rows; either ships a corpus with fewer than 90 dropped rows (failing AC floor) or invents a definition inconsistent with the TP/FP semantics","Kappa computation has insufficient 'TP for dropped' rows to be meaningful, undermining the validity gate"],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"In Step 3, add: 'Dropped findings are sourced from criterion-level PASS verdict rows in REVIEW_RESULT sidecar payloads (each row where verdict=PASS and no finding text was emitted is one dropped finding; TP=correctly not surfaced, FP=a real defect missed). The sampling script extracts these from the same sidecar files used for surfaced findings.'","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"medium","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"high"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Extend the `post_claim_edit_class` definition in Step 1 to explicitly handle tickets with `reopen_count > 0`: state whether subsequent `in_progress` windows are also included in the post-claim window, or only the first-claim-to-close span is used, so the field is reproducible for all tickets in the corpus.","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"block","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan: 'An edit is post-claim iff its event timestamp falls between the ticket's first transition-into-`in_progress` and its close'","Plan schema includes `reopen_count (int)` as a field, confirming reopened tickets exist in the corpus","No rule given for edits in second/subsequent in_progress windows on the same ticket"],"finding":"The `post_claim_edit_class` assignment is ambiguous for tickets with reopen events. The plan defines the post-claim window as 'between the ticket's first transition-into-`in_progress` and its close,' and the schema includes `reopen_count`. For a ticket reopened and reclaimed (reopen_count > 0), there is a second in_progress window before final close. The plan does not specify whether description edits during subsequent claim windows count as post-claim, whether each reclaim resets the window, or whether only edits in the original first-claim window apply. This makes `post_claim_edit_class` non-reproducible for the significant fraction of tickets with reopen events.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f03903d730611dc7c","impact":0.67,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 1 (Mine the outcome corpus) — post_claim_edit_class definition paragraph","norm_id":"ne6cddf868e875a3f","priority":0.67,"reason":"high-priority+criterion-opted-in","scenarios":["Two implementers classify the same reopened ticket differently — one uses only the first-claim window, the other treats any in_progress period as a claim window — producing non-reproducible corpora","§5 re-verification (Step 2) yields different edit counts depending on the window interpretation, creating false CORRECTED-TO markers"],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"Add: 'For tickets with reopen_count > 0, the post-claim window spans from the ticket's *first* transition-into-`in_progress` to its *final* close, inclusive of all intervening editing periods (reopen and reclaim events do not reset the window).'","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Inline the §5.2 classification decision rules into Step 1 (or a linked appendix in the README spec): define precedence order for overlapping classes and provide at least one distinguishing example for the ambiguous pairs (`operator-attested-retag` vs. `cosmetic`; `plan-authored-post-claim` vs. `approach-change`).","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"block","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan states: 'the §5.2 taxonomy' as the source of classification rules, but §5.2 is only referenced — not reproduced or summarized.","The 8 labels are listed, but no rule specifying which label takes precedence when multiple could apply (e.g., an edit that both changes approach and reduces scope) is given.","Search confirms 'operator-attested-retag' appears nowhere in the codebase outside this plan, meaning there is no existing definition the executor can reference."],"finding":"The `post_claim_edit_class` taxonomy (8 values) is defined in the plan, but the decision rules for distinguishing between overlapping classes — especially `operator-attested-retag` vs. `cosmetic`, and `plan-authored-post-claim` vs. `approach-change` — are attributed to '§5.2 taxonomy' (an external report section not included in the plan). An executor building `mine_outcome_corpus.py` cannot classify edits without reading that external document, violating instruction-locality.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f5b60e7ce1471757c","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 1 ('`post_claim_edit_class` closed vocabulary (the §5.2 taxonomy; exactly one per row)')","norm_id":"n75849daf04c52898","priority":1.0,"reason":"high-priority+criterion-opted-in","scenarios":["An edit that removes two acceptance criteria (scope-reduction) also changes the implementation approach (approach-change) — without a precedence rule the mining script author must guess, producing non-reproducible classifications.","An operator comment retagging a post-claim edit as 'cosmetic' could be classified as either `operator-attested-retag` or `cosmetic` with no distinguishing rule in the plan."],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"high"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Name and scope a committed adjudication corpus builder script (e.g., harnesses/build_adjudication_corpus.py) in both the Scope section and the AC proving command, mirroring the pattern established for mine_outcome_corpus.py (with --dry-run, documented CLI flags, and exact regeneration command in the README).","cohort":["T5b","T5e","T9"],"criteria":["T9"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Scope names 'harnesses/mine_outcome_corpus.py (new)' explicitly but lists only 'adjudicate_rubric_a.md, adjudicate_rubric_b.md, and kappa.py' for adjudication — no adjudication corpus builder script is named","AC says 'runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl is committed' but no proving command names the script that creates it, unlike AC bullet 1 which names mine_outcome_corpus.py --dry-run"],"finding":"The script responsible for creating adjudication_corpus.jsonl is never named in the plan (unlike mine_outcome_corpus.py for the outcome corpus), so the CREATE ownership, invocation interface, and CLI flags (e.g., --dry-run, --stratify-by-criterion) for this corpus are undefined, making it impossible to reproduce or audit the corpus build.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fac4b1f9f0b0e2e6b","impact":0.85,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 3; Scope section (harnesses/ list)","norm_id":"nfc8ae1ca4ee2040f","priority":0.85,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["A future maintainer needs to regenerate adjudication_corpus.jsonl after new tickets are added; there is no named script to run","Audit of corpus provenance cannot trace the stratification logic or LLM prompt version to a committed artifact"],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"medium","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Clarify that the pre-flight probe must parse `git rev-list --objects --all` output and filter to blob objects that parse as ticket-genesis events (or use `rebar list --status=closed,open,in_progress | wc -l` via the CLI) — not use raw `--count` on total objects — to correctly count recoverable reviewed tickets.","cohort":["T3"],"criteria":["T3"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan phrase: 'the script runs git rev-list --count --objects --all and counts recovered ticket-genesis events'","git rev-list --count --objects --all counts ALL objects (commits + trees + blobs), not typed-event records; ticket-genesis events are a small typed subset that requires filtering on blob content, not a raw object-count check","Evidence class: Unverified — the flag combination exists and is valid git plumbing, but the semantics the plan asserts (genesis-event count) are not what the command delivers without additional parsing"],"finding":"The plan's pre-flight object-availability probe (`git rev-list --count --objects --all`) cannot count 'recovered ticket-genesis events' as asserted — it returns the total object count across all object types (commits, trees, blobs), not a filtered genesis-event count. A truncated history with few ticket-genesis events but many non-event objects could pass the floor of 500 even when the actual recoverable ticket corpus is small.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"ff0257b18b4099f49","impact":0.85,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 1 — 'Pre-flight object-availability probe (mandatory)': 'runs git rev-list --count --objects --all and counts recovered ticket-genesis events; if the recovered reviewed-ticket count falls below a floor of 500…'","norm_id":"n54557e89a66dc6de","priority":0.85,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["A repo where git gc has pruned old ticket blobs but packed many non-ticket objects could have total --count >> 500 while actual recoverable reviewed-ticket genesis events number far below 500, silently passing the probe and producing a truncated corpus","The pre-flight guard — the plan's own safety net — fails to provide the asserted protection"],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"Replace the raw `git rev-list --count --objects --all` count with either: (a) `rebar list --status=closed,in_progress,open | python -c 'import sys,json; print(len(json.load(sys.stdin)))'` as the ticket count source, or (b) stream-parse `git rev-list --objects --all` output and count only blobs whose content parses as a CREATE/CLAIM event for a reviewed ticket.","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"medium","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Co-locate the computation protocol for `had_persisted_review` with the schema definition in Step 1: specify whether it is derived from git-object history (`git cat-file` scan for any `REVIEW_RESULT` event) or from current disk state, and state the behavior when the sidecar was pruned by the retention cap.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan states schema includes `had_persisted_review (bool)` but gives no definition of how to compute it.","Tests show REVIEW_RESULT sidecars are subject to a retention prune (test_audit_retention_cap.py), meaning on-disk presence is not a reliable proxy for 'has ever had a persisted review'.","Step 1 says history is recovered via `git cat-file` from git objects, but does not clarify whether `had_persisted_review` should be derived from git-object history (authoritative) or current disk state (lossy after pruning)."],"finding":"The `had_persisted_review` field in the outcome-corpus schema (Step 1) is load-bearing for Step 3 (only tickets where `had_persisted_review=true` contribute to the adjudication corpus), but the computing protocol for `had_persisted_review` is not co-located with the schema definition — specifically: what constitutes a 'persisted review' (a `REVIEW_RESULT` event file on disk? in git objects? via `rebar show`?) is never stated, and the plan does not specify what to do if the sidecar is present in git objects but was pruned from disk by the retention cap.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f2df6a10fbfb039aa","impact":0.67,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 1 (outcome-corpus schema: `had_persisted_review (bool)`); Step 3 ('drawn from the persisted REVIEW_RESULT sidecars')","norm_id":"n421b8dcd01d67567","priority":0.67,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["A ticket had a REVIEW_RESULT sidecar that was pruned by the retention cap — on-disk it is absent, but in git-objects it exists. The mining script sets `had_persisted_review=false`, excluding it from the adjudication corpus, silently under-populating the sample."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"Add to the schema description: '`had_persisted_review`: true iff at least one `*-REVIEW_RESULT.json` file for this ticket_id appears in the git-object graph (recovered via `git cat-file`), regardless of current disk presence (retention-pruned sidecars count as persisted).'.","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T3"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan's core data-recovery method (`git rev-list --objects --all` on the tickets branch) asserts it can re-derive §5 event history from git objects, but the plan itself states 'the on-disk .tickets-tracker/ is compacted' — if the tickets branch has been force-pushed, rebased, squash-merged, or subjected to `git gc` pruning unreachable objects, the historical event blobs may be permanently gone. The only named fallback ('ephemeral prior artifacts may exist at /Users/joeoakhart/.claude/jobs/e5b41784/tmp/') is explicitly uncertain and non-reproducible, leaving the AC-1 regeneration-command requirement and AC-2 re-verification with no achievable path if the objects are absent.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f4499a8fb0372bf30","impact":0.85,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'Re-derive the §5 event history from git objects across all refs of the tickets branch (git rev-list --objects --all + cat-file; the on-disk .tickets-tracker/ is compacted) - method in report §5; ephemeral prior artifacts may exist at /Users/joeoakhart/.claude/jobs/e5b41784/tmp/ but the corpus must be reproducible without them.'","norm_id":"n1c7c4814b551ad09","priority":0.6611,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":[],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"Add a pre-flight step to the mining script: run `git rev-list --objects --all | git cat-file --batch-check | grep -c blob` and assert the count is plausible (e.g., > 5000 blobs). If it fails, switch to the rebar ticket-read API (already available in this repo) to reconstruct event history from live ticket state, and document both paths in the README.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.7778,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"medium","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"medium","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"hard","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a minimum-content specification for each adjudication rubric (e.g. must include: the TP/FP definition verbatim, per-criterion guidance, and at least N worked examples) so an executor can produce a conforming rubric without a design decision.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E2"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Rater A (primary): an LLM adjudicator run with rubric harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md'","'Rater B (independent): a second LLM adjudicator with an independently-authored rubric harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_b.md'","No content requirements, section headings, or acceptance bar for the rubrics are stated anywhere in the plan."],"finding":"The content and quality requirements for `adjudicate_rubric_a.md` and `adjudicate_rubric_b.md` are completely unspecified. The plan lists them as new deliverables but gives no guidance on required sections, prompt structure, or what makes them 'independently authored'. An executor must 'choose an appropriate rubric' — a real design decision deferred to runtime.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f159fc6bf72cfea57","impact":0.67,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 4 — 'Double-label'; Scope bullet for harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md and adjudicate_rubric_b.md","norm_id":"n245b2ed785940970","priority":0.5863,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Two different executors produce radically different rubrics, leading to incomparable kappa values across runs; a rubric that trivially labels everything TP passes AC4 because kappa is still computed."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.875,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a minimum content specification for adjudicate_rubric_a.md and adjudicate_rubric_b.md to the plan (e.g., each rubric must define the TP/FP/ambiguous labels by referencing the README vocabulary, state the criterion scope it covers, and include at least two worked examples); require the README to record that both rubrics were reviewed against this spec before use.","cohort":["T2","T4","T7"],"criteria":["T7"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Rater A (primary): an LLM adjudicator run with rubric harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md' — no content requirements stated","'a second LLM adjudicator with an independently-authored rubric harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_b.md' — 'independently authored' is the only specification","The README schema documentation requirements (schema, vocabularies, kappa, provenance) are detailed, but no parallel documentation requirement is stated for the rubric files themselves","ABSENCE: no rubric content checklist, no requirement that rubrics reference the §5.2 taxonomy or the closed tp_fp vocabulary, no review step before use"],"finding":"The two adjudicator rubric files (adjudicate_rubric_a.md and adjudicate_rubric_b.md) are new contract-defining artifacts that govern all LLM rater behavior and therefore the kappa outcome, but the plan specifies neither their required content/structure nor any quality-validation step before they are used — they are simply listed as new files with no doc standard applied to them.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fac228730921f4dbe","impact":0.67,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section: 'harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md, adjudicate_rubric_b.md, and kappa.py (new)'; Step 4","norm_id":"n74ac87070ba49f68","priority":0.5863,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Rubrics omit the tp_fp TP/FP/ambiguous vocabulary definition, causing rater labeling to diverge from the corpus schema","Rubric B is so similar to Rubric A (or so vague) that kappa is artificially inflated, making the gate meaningless","Rubric content cannot be audited or reproduced because no structure requirement was committed alongside the files"],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"In the Scope section, add: 'Each rubric must (a) reproduce or cite the tp_fp vocabulary from the README, (b) state which criterion ids it covers, and (c) include ≥2 worked canonical examples (one TP, one FP). The README records that both rubrics satisfy this spec.' This gives auditors a concrete artifact to check without over-specifying the rubric prose.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.875,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a required-content spec for both rubric files in Step 4 or Scope: minimum sections (definition of TP/FP with ≥2 worked examples per class, output format, tie-breaking rules, calibration anchor), and state that `adjudicate_rubric_b.md` must not share any examples or framing from rubric A.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan says 'an LLM adjudicator run with rubric harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md' and 'independently-authored rubric harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_b.md' — but no content requirements are given for either file.","Directory listing confirms neither file exists in the repo under docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/ (directory listing shows only experimental .py files, no rubric .md files).","The kappa value is entirely determined by how these rubrics instruct the LLMs to classify; an under-specified rubric can trivially inflate or deflate kappa, making the validity gate meaningless."],"finding":"The two LLM adjudicator rubric files (`adjudicate_rubric_a.md` and `adjudicate_rubric_b.md`) are designated deliverables that govern all rater behavior and therefore the kappa outcome, yet the plan specifies zero structural requirements for their content — no required sections, no definition of what counts as 'spurious', no calibration examples, no output-format constraint, no tie-breaking rules. The plan mentions them only by name, leaving an executor to author them from scratch with no specification.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fd2f717e7283c0bbd","impact":0.67,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 4 ('Rater A (primary)' and 'Rater B (independent)' sub-bullets); Scope section ('adjudicate_rubric_a.md, adjudicate_rubric_b.md, and kappa.py (new)')","norm_id":"n30eed7377f3239bb","priority":0.5863,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["An executor writes adjudicate_rubric_a.md with a loose definition of 'spurious finding', and adjudicate_rubric_b.md with a strict one — kappa drops below 0.7 due to specification ambiguity, not rater disagreement.","Both rubrics omit output format requirements, so Rater A emits prose labels and Rater B emits JSON — kappa.py cannot parse them consistently."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.875,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify the blind-labeling protocol co-located with the Rater B description in Step 4: state which fields are stripped before Rater B sees a finding (at minimum: `rater_a`, `tp_fp`), whether `rationale` is also stripped, and how the stripped subset is persisted (e.g., a separate `rater_b_input.jsonl` with only `finding_id`, `ticket_id`, `criterion`, `source`, `decision`, and the finding text).","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan says Rater B labels 'BLIND to Rater A's labels' but specifies no mechanism: no field-stripping protocol, no separate input file, no mention of removing rationale that could carry implicit label signal.","The adjudication-corpus schema (Step 3) places `rater_a`, `rater_b`, `tp_fp`, and `rationale` in the same row — an executor could accidentally pass the full row (with `rater_a` populated) to Rater B's prompt."],"finding":"Step 4 specifies that Rater B labels a 'stratified-by-criterion ≥50-finding subset BLIND to Rater A's labels', but provides no protocol for how the blind condition is mechanically enforced — the plan does not specify whether Rater A's labels are stripped from the JSONL before Rater B's prompt is constructed, whether `rater_a` is simply omitted from the Rater B input, or how the corpus-builder prevents label leakage via rationale text that implicitly encodes the TP/FP verdict.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f01efc6c7f90f94fc","impact":0.67,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 4 ('Rater B (independent)' sub-bullet: 're-labels a stratified-by-criterion ≥50-finding subset BLIND to Rater A's labels')","norm_id":"ncd04d99b0d7c038b","priority":0.5863,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["The corpus-builder passes the full adjudication_corpus.jsonl row to Rater B's prompt with `rater_a` populated — Rater B is not actually blind, inflating kappa artificially.","The `rationale` field (populated by Rater A) uses language that implicitly signals TP or FP ('clearly spurious', 'genuine defect') — Rater B reads the rationale and echoes the same verdict, artificially inflating kappa."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"Add: 'Rater B receives a stripped view containing only `finding_id`, `criterion`, `source`, `decision`, and the finding text (fields `rater_a`, `tp_fp`, and `rationale` are omitted); this stripped file is committed as `runs/rater_b_input.jsonl` for reproducibility.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.875,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a `jq`-based schema-validation step to AC1's proving command that asserts every row contains all five required fields (e.g. `jq -e 'select(.post_claim_edit_class and .reopen_count != null and .force_close != null and .completion_verifier_fail_count != null and .review_round_count != null)' runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl | wc -l` equals the total line count).","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Proving command: python .../mine_outcome_corpus.py --dry-run exits 0 and wc -l runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl ≥ 500'","AC1 text: 'one row per reviewed ticket carrying post_claim_edit_class, reopen_count, force_close, completion_verifier_fail_count, and review_round_count'","No jq schema-validation command is present in AC1."],"finding":"AC1's proving command (`wc -l runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl ≥ 500`) only validates row count, not schema. A corpus with 500 rows that are all missing `post_claim_edit_class`, `reopen_count`, `force_close`, `completion_verifier_fail_count`, or `review_round_count` would silently pass the AC.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fd2c3fd12bc39c968","impact":0.55,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC1 proving command","norm_id":"n26750ec5e294ae18","priority":0.55,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["A bug in mine_outcome_corpus.py omits a required field from every row; the wc -l check passes and the corpus is declared done, but downstream E2/E3/E6 consumers fail when the field is absent."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"jq -e '[.post_claim_edit_class, .reopen_count, .force_close, .completion_verifier_fail_count, .review_round_count] | all(. != null)' runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl | grep -c true | xargs -I{} sh -c '[ {} -ge 500 ]'","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a concrete grep/awk command to AC2's proving command that asserts the README contains at least the required number of AGREES or CORRECTED-TO markers (one per re-derived figure), e.g. `grep -cE 'AGREES|CORRECTED-TO' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/README.md | xargs -I{} sh -c '[ {} -ge 7 ]'`.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Proving command: python .../mine_outcome_corpus.py --verify-s5 prints the derived figures and the table in README names each as agreeing or corrected (no figure left as \"agreement OR corrected\")'","No grep or jq command checks the README content for required markers."],"finding":"AC2's proving command (`mine_outcome_corpus.py --verify-s5` prints figures) does not include any machine-checkable assertion that the README's re-verification table actually contains the required AGREES/CORRECTED-TO markers per figure. The README check is left as implicit human inspection.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fbbe04115d12cf59f","impact":0.55,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2 proving command","norm_id":"n7a1e9133609a3ca7","priority":0.55,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["A README is committed with a narrative description of figures but no per-figure AGREES/CORRECTED-TO label; --verify-s5 still exits 0 because it only checks the script output, not the README."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"grep -cE '\\b(AGREES|CORRECTED-TO)\\b' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/README.md | xargs -I{} sh -c '[ {} -ge 7 ]'","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an AC (or a --dry-run --simulate-gc mode) that exercises the pre-flight probe's failure path: verify the script exits non-zero, prints the specified error message, and leaves no output file when the recovered ticket count is below the 500 floor.","cohort":["E5","G5"],"criteria":["E5"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'if the recovered reviewed-ticket count falls below a floor of 500 (expected ~527), it halts with an actionable error (gc/pruned objects — history incomplete) and writes nothing'","AC1 proving command only tests: `python .../mine_outcome_corpus.py --dry-run` exits 0 and `wc -l runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl` ≥ 500","No AC covers the probe's failure branch: exit non-zero, correct error message, and zero bytes written to the output file","The probe is labeled '(mandatory)' in the plan, indicating it is the primary safety mechanism against silently truncated corpora"],"finding":"The pre-flight object-availability probe's failure path — halting with an error and writing nothing when the recovered-ticket count falls below 500 — has no AC coverage; only the happy path (--dry-run exits 0, wc -l ≥ 500) is proven.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"faeb4424bbdc36ac6","impact":0.55,"is_primary":null,"location":"## What, Step 1 (Pre-flight object-availability probe) and AC line 1 (Proving command: `--dry-run` exits 0, `wc -l` ≥ 500)","norm_id":"n408d59cc4a6fea0d","priority":0.55,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["A gc'd or partially-pruned repo runs the script, the probe fires, but a bug causes it to continue anyway and write a truncated corpus — no AC would catch this regression.","The script exits non-zero but still writes a partial .tmp file that is not cleaned up — no AC verifies the 'writes nothing' guarantee."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"Add to AC1: 'Proving command (failure path): run the script with a mocked/overridden count below 500 (e.g. `--max-objects 400` flag or a unit test patching the count) and assert exit code ≠ 0, the error message contains \"gc/pruned objects\", and `outcome_corpus.jsonl` does not exist.'","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Replace the AC3 proving command placeholder with a concrete, copy-paste-executable jq command that (a) asserts `source`, `tp_fp`, and `rationale` are present on every row and (b) asserts the surfaced count ≥ 280 and dropped count ≥ 90.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6","F1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Proving command: a jq/python check that every row has source, tp_fp, rationale and the surfaced/dropped counts meet the floor'","No actual jq expression or python invocation is written out."],"finding":"AC3's proving command is described only as 'a jq/python check' — no concrete expression is given. This is a placeholder, not a concrete proving command, and cannot be executed without further authoring by the executor.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"ffa90c0998fba5072","impact":0.44,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC3 proving command","norm_id":"n340dcabc167a048c","priority":0.44,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Executor writes a minimal check that only tests one field and misses the count floor; or two executors write incompatible checks producing different pass/fail results."],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"jq -s '[.[] | select(.source==\"surfaced\")] | length' runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl | xargs -I{} sh -c '[ {} -ge 280 ]' && jq -s '[.[] | select(.source==\"dropped\")] | length' runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl | xargs -I{} sh -c '[ {} -ge 90 ]' && jq -e 'select(.source and .tp_fp and .rationale)' runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl > /dev/null","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":null,"blocking_enabled":null,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["P6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["4 criterion line(s) bundle multiple deliverables with 'and' (split so each is independently verifiable).","verify command `wc -l runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl` inspects output with `wc` but asserts nothing — add an exit-code or comparison (-q, [ \"$(...)\" -eq N ], jq -e) so a failure is observable"],"finding":"Acceptance-criteria / definition-of-done quality issues.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f607dd457c67f9209","impact":0.4,"is_primary":null,"location":"","norm_id":"ned06ebc801a522e3","priority":0.4,"reason":null,"scenarios":[],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Split compound criteria, replace subjective terms with observable outcomes, and state how each is verified.","tier":"DET","validity":1.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an AC (or extend AC4) requiring that `harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md` and `harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_b.md` are committed, non-empty, and explicitly reference the TP/FP vocabulary (e.g. `grep -q 'TP\\|FP' harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_{a,b}.md` exits 0).","cohort":["COH","E1","T5d"],"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Scope: 'harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md, adjudicate_rubric_b.md … (new)'","Step 4: 'Rater A … run with rubric harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md'; 'Rater B … independently-authored rubric harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_b.md'","AC4 proving command: 'python .../kappa.py runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl' — no check on rubric file existence or content"],"finding":"The Scope explicitly names `harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md` and `harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_b.md` as new deliverables, but no AC verifies these files are committed (non-empty, referencing the correct TP/FP vocabulary). Step 4 depends on them being correct, but the proving commands only invoke `kappa.py` — a passing kappa run does not verify the rubric files exist or are coherent.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f4a95e06dab793b45","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section (harness file list) vs AC4 proving command","norm_id":"na27608466f59928f","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Rubric files are committed as empty stubs or with the wrong vocabulary (block-worthy instead of TP/FP); kappa.py still passes because it only reads adjudication_corpus.jsonl; downstream E2/E3/E6 ingest rubrics that were never validated."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.875,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify that adjudication_corpus.jsonl is written atomically (via .tmp+os.replace), that the adjudication script checkpoints per-finding to a .partial file so re-runs resume rather than restart, and that LLM call failures surface an explicit error (with count of completed vs. expected rows) rather than silently producing a truncated corpus.","cohort":["T5b","T5e","T9"],"criteria":["T5b"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["ABSENCE: the plan specifies .tmp+os.replace atomicity only for outcome_corpus.jsonl, not for adjudication_corpus.jsonl","ABSENCE: no retry/backoff/resume strategy is mentioned for LLM rater calls","Step 4 describes Rater A labeling 'the full sample' and Rater B labeling '≥50-finding subset' with no mention of checkpointing or error recovery"],"finding":"The adjudication corpus build (Rater A and Rater B LLM calls labeling ~400 findings) has no specified error handling, retry, or partial-state recovery strategy; if any LLM call fails mid-run, the script's behavior — whether it crashes, skips, or writes a partial adjudication_corpus.jsonl — is undefined, potentially shipping a silently truncated or inconsistent corpus to downstream E2/E3/E6 consumers.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f4fe137c190edcc1d","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 3 / Step 4 (adjudication corpus build and double-labeling); Scope section adjudicate_rubric_a/b.md","norm_id":"n636e8ce6dfa2cf6b","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["LLM API returns a 5xx mid-run after 200 of 400 findings are labeled; script crashes; adjudication_corpus.jsonl contains 200 rows and is committed as if complete","Rater B call times out; kappa.py is run on an undersized double-labeled subset; kappa passes spuriously due to small N"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a per-finding checkpoint file (e.g., runs/adjudication_corpus.partial.jsonl) that the adjudication script appends to atomically; on completion, it renames to adjudication_corpus.jsonl. On re-run, already-labeled finding_ids are skipped. LLM HTTP errors trigger up to 3 retries with exponential backoff; exhausted retries write the finding with tp_fp=null and a rationale noting the failure, so the corpus row count is always complete and the kappa script can report the null-fraction.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.625,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Verify that commit '143d5074e' exists and is reachable (specify which git repo/branch), or replace it with the correct commit SHA that contains the §5 report, so the README provenance anchor is reproducible.","cohort":["G1G2"],"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Search for '143d5074e' across all repo files returns zero matches.","ABSENCE: the commit SHA appears only in the plan text itself, with no corroborating reference in any existing file, CHANGELOG, or doc."],"finding":"The Scope section states runs/README.md must record 'the provenance (report commit 143d5074e, this store's tickets branch)' — but the commit SHA '143d5074e' is not found anywhere in the repository's text files. If this commit does not exist in git history, the provenance anchor in the README cannot be reproduced or verified.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fcedabe2c81fda96e","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section: 'runs/README.md (new/extended): ... the provenance (report commit 143d5074e, this store's tickets branch)'","norm_id":"n081ec130b1e2d696","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["An executor writes the README with this SHA, but the commit doesn't exist in the local git history — the provenance record is then unfalsifiable and the 'exact regeneration commands' AC cannot be satisfied.","The SHA may reference a commit in a different branch (e.g., the tickets branch) that is not accessible from the code repo; if so, the plan must say which repo/branch."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Acknowledge the correlated-error risk of same-provider LLM raters in the README and add at least one mitigation: either (a) require Rater B to be from a different provider family, (b) spot-check a random 20-finding human-labeled slice as an external anchor, or (c) record the model identities and flag the kappa value as 'LLM-only kappa (provider-correlated)' rather than treating it equivalently to human IRR.","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan Step 4: 'a second LLM adjudicator with an independently-authored rubric and a different model (e.g. a distinct Claude model id from Rater A)'","'e.g. a distinct Claude model id' means both raters could be Claude variants with shared systematic biases","Plan Step 5: 'kappa ≥ 0.7 → labels are declared usable ground truth' — no qualification about correlated LLM errors","No mention of cross-validation against human labels or acknowledgment of the same-provider correlation risk"],"finding":"The two-LLM kappa gate (Step 4/5) does not adequately solve the named validity problem because same-provider LLMs share training-data and RLHF-induced biases, causing their labeling errors to be correlated. A kappa ≥ 0.7 achieved by two Claude model variants can reflect shared systematic bias rather than independent convergence, making the validity declaration ('labels are usable ground truth') a false positive. The plan offers no acknowledgment of or mitigation for this limitation.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fe03792939ad64dd0","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 4 (Double-label and compute inter-rater reliability); Step 5 (Apply the validity gate)","norm_id":"nee484ffddbf9909a","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Both LLM raters systematically over-label 'ambiguous' findings from a particular criterion as TP due to shared training bias; kappa reaches 0.8 but the labels are systematically wrong; downstream E2/E3 precision metrics are polluted","kappa < 0.7 is achieved only when the two LLMs happen to differ in a specific failure mode, not when labels are genuinely wrong — the gate provides false confidence"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Justify the dual-LLM-same-provider inter-rater design against the prior art on LLM annotation independence (e.g., Gilardi 2023, Zheng 2023), and either switch at least one rater to a cross-provider model or a human, or explicitly bound the interpretation of kappa under correlated-rater conditions.","cohort":["T1"],"criteria":["T1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'a second LLM adjudicator with an independently-authored rubric ... and a **different model** (e.g. a distinct Claude model id from Rater A)'","Absence: no justification of LLM-as-rater vs established alternatives (human rater, cross-provider rater)","Absence: no acknowledgment that same-provider LLMs share systematic biases that violate kappa's independence assumption","Prior art: Gilardi et al. (2023) 'ChatGPT Outperforms Crowd Workers for Text-Annotation Tasks' and follow-on work note intra-family agreement inflation as a validity threat"],"finding":"The plan specifies two independent LLM raters from the same provider family ('a distinct Claude model id from Rater A') as the basis for a Cohen's kappa validity gate, but does not acknowledge or justify this choice against the established prior art on LLM-as-annotator reliability. The relevant literature (Gilardi et al. 2023, Zheng et al. 2023) specifically identifies intra-family systematic bias as a threat to independence — two Claude models share training data, RLHF calibration, and rubric interpretation patterns. This inflates pairwise agreement, making a kappa ≥ 0.7 gate uninterpretable as evidence of ground-truth validity, which is the entire purpose of Step 5.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f0f036edf8f6eeb1f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 4 (Double-label and compute inter-rater reliability) / AC#4","norm_id":"n7b18979c904bff3e","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Both Claude models agree at high rates due to shared RLHF calibration; kappa clears 0.7 but reflects correlated noise rather than genuine label reliability; downstream E2/E3/E6 and R1/R7 are built on a spurious ground-truth signal.","A post-hoc audit finds the kappa gate was gamed by intra-family correlation, requiring the corpus to be re-adjudicated with genuinely independent raters."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify the kappa.py dependency explicitly (e.g., 'uses `sklearn.metrics.cohen_kappa_score`' or 'inline two-class formula per Cohen 1960') and confirm the dependency is available in the project's environment.","cohort":["T1"],"criteria":["T1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'a committed script harnesses/kappa.py computes **Cohen's kappa**'","Absence: no named dependency (scikit-learn, scipy, or inline formula) specified anywhere in the plan","No existing kappa.py found in docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/ — the script does not yet exist to inspect"],"finding":"The plan specifies a committed `harnesses/kappa.py` that computes Cohen's kappa, but names no Python library or implementation approach for that computation. `scikit-learn` (the standard source of `cohen_kappa_score`) is unresolved in the installed environment and may not be available in this repo's dependency set. The plan does not verify this capability.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f617781c4b18827c6","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 4 / Scope section ('harnesses/kappa.py (new)')","norm_id":"n78e0672b99fd9540","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["The implementer writes kappa.py and discovers scikit-learn is not in the project's requirements, causing an import error at proving-command time.","The implementer hand-rolls kappa with a subtle formula error (e.g., mishandling the ambiguous-excluded-pairwise logic), and the README records an incorrect value with no way to audit it."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add to the Scope section: 'kappa.py uses `sklearn.metrics.cohen_kappa_score`; scikit-learn must be listed in the project's dev dependencies or the script must bundle a two-line inline formula for the binary case.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Verify that `rebar show <ticket_id>` output actually emits `reopen_count`, `force_close`, `completion_verifier_fail_count`, and `review_round_count` (e.g. by running against a known test ticket and inspecting stdout), or specify the alternative derivation path (e.g. counting STATUS events from git history for reopen_count) if these are not emitted by the CLI.","cohort":["T3"],"criteria":["T3"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["src/rebar/schemas/ticket_state.schema.json lists required fields: ticket_id, ticket_type, title, status, priority, tags — none of the four corpus fields appear","The schema has 'additionalProperties: true', so fields COULD exist via event replay, but they are not confirmed as emitted","Only 'last_reopened_at' (timestamp, not a count) is documented for reopen state","Evidence class: Unverified — rebar show CLI confirmed to exist (tests/golden/cli_help/show__help.out), but the specific four corpus fields are not confirmed in schema or any golden output"],"finding":"The plan asserts that four corpus schema fields — `reopen_count` (int), `force_close` (bool), `completion_verifier_fail_count` (int), and `review_round_count` (int) — are readable from `rebar show` CLI output, but none of these fields appear in `src/rebar/schemas/ticket_state.schema.json`. The schema documents only `last_reopened_at` (a ns-epoch timestamp) for reopen-related state, and has no documented fields for verifier-fail or review-round counts.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fac5ae0fbd8d13f44","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 1 — Outcome-corpus schema; also AC#1: 'one row per reviewed ticket carrying reopen_count, force_close, completion_verifier_fail_count, and review_round_count'; Step 1 body: 'Current-state fields … are read via the rebar show CLI'","norm_id":"nae33adddf2698901","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["If rebar show does not emit reopen_count / force_close / completion_verifier_fail_count / review_round_count, the mining script fails or silently emits null for all corpus rows, invalidating the outcome corpus and blocking downstream E2/E3/E6 and R1/R7 work","The AC#1 proving command (`wc -l runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl >= 500`) would pass even with all four fields null, masking the gap"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.8889,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"insufficient","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"medium","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T2"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan's git-mining method (git rev-list --objects --all + cat-file on the tickets branch) is an unverified assumption about the git repo's object availability. The plan acknowledges the on-disk .tickets-tracker/ is compacted and that ephemeral artifacts 'may' exist, but does not include a pre-corpus probe confirming that git objects across all refs actually retain enough history to reconstruct the 16/505 edits and 3-miss defect-class events. If the repo has been gc'd, pruned, or force-pushed, the reconstruction silently produces incomplete or incorrect counts — and the corpus is committed with wrong labels.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"faa68c33f624967e7","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'Re-derive the §5 event history from git objects across all refs of the tickets branch (git rev-list --objects --all + cat-file; the on-disk .tickets-tracker/ is compacted)'","norm_id":"n8dffccab8fa6bce4","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Insert an AC-0 or 'Definition of Ready' step: run `git rev-list --objects --all -- .tickets-tracker/ | wc -l` and compare against an expected lower bound (derived from the known ~527 ticket count); if the count falls below threshold, the mining approach is declared infeasible and the plan documents an alternative source (e.g., the ephemeral /tmp/ snapshot or a manually reconstructed sample) before proceeding.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.8889,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Expose the kappa threshold, ticket floor, and sample floors as CLI arguments with the current values as defaults (e.g., --kappa-threshold 0.7, --ticket-floor 500, --min-surfaced 280, --min-dropped 90) so the scripts remain usable as the experiment evolves without source edits.","cohort":["T5b","T5e","T9"],"criteria":["T5e"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'kappa ≥ 0.7 → labels are declared usable ground truth'","'if the recovered reviewed-ticket count falls below a floor of 500'","'Floor for the AC: ≥280 surfaced and ≥90 dropped'","ABSENCE: no --kappa-threshold, --ticket-floor, or --sample-floor CLI arguments mentioned"],"finding":"The kappa threshold (≥ 0.7), the outcome corpus ticket floor (500), and the adjudication sample floors (≥280 surfaced, ≥90 dropped) are hardcoded throughout the plan and will be embedded as literals in the committed scripts; these are experimental parameters that are likely to be revisited as the corpus grows or the methodology evolves, but the plan provides no mechanism (CLI flags or config) to adjust them without editing source.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f83953075ee97413f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 5 (kappa gate); AC bullet 1 (floor 500); AC bullet 3 (floors 280/90); harnesses/kappa.py","norm_id":"nbef8692e8536bef0","priority":0.0,"reason":"low-validity","scenarios":["The experiment is scaled up to 1000 tickets; the floor of 500 must be changed by editing kappa.py and mine_outcome_corpus.py source","A follow-on story lowers the kappa gate to 0.6 for a specific criterion subset; requires code change rather than a config argument"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In kappa.py: add argparse argument --kappa-threshold (default=0.7). In mine_outcome_corpus.py: add --ticket-floor (default=500). Document these defaults in the README's regeneration commands so the defaults are auditable.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.3333,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"na","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Consider whether the outcome corpus (steps 1-2, unblocking E2/E3/E6) and the adjudication corpus + kappa gate (steps 3-5, unblocking R1/R7) are independently valuable enough to split into two child tickets, or explicitly document why they must ship together.","cohort":["E5","G5"],"criteria":["G5"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Steps 1-2 produce `outcome_corpus.jsonl` and serve 'E2/E3/E6'","Steps 3-5 produce `adjudication_corpus.jsonl` + kappa and serve 'R1/R7'","The plan itself names both consumer groups: 'finding-level TP/FP labels needed by E2/E3/E6 and R1/R7'","Each artifact could be committed and consumed independently — releasing only the outcome corpus would unblock E2/E3/E6 while R1/R7 work proceeds in parallel"],"finding":"The ticket bundles two independently-releasable artifacts — the outcome corpus (unblocking E2/E3/E6) and the finding-adjudication corpus + kappa gate (unblocking R1/R7) — each serving a distinct downstream consumer, potentially warranting separate child stories.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f3b3510a96bae0692","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"## What (steps 1-2 vs. steps 3-5) and ## Scope","norm_id":"nef302171a7784f1e","priority":0.0,"reason":"low-validity","scenarios":["If the kappa gate fails (kappa < 0.7), the outcome corpus work is already complete and usable, but both are held in one ticket and must be re-opened/re-worked together.","If the adjudication corpus sampling reveals a population too small (fewer than 90 dropped findings available), the outcome corpus — which is independently useful — is stalled."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.4286,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add one sentence in Step 1 (or the Scope rationale for `mine_outcome_corpus.py`) stating why git-object recovery is required for `post_claim_edit_class` derivation — specifically that the compacted `.tickets-tracker/` exposes no per-event description-diff history via the rebar CLI, making git-object traversal the only path to recovering the edit timeline between claim and close.","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan Step 1: 'Event history is recovered from git objects on the tickets branch (the on-disk `.tickets-tracker/` is compacted): `git rev-list --objects --all` + `git cat-file` (method in report §5)'","'Current-state fields (reopen/force-close/verifier-fail/round counts) are read via the `rebar show` CLI' — confirming a hybrid approach is already used, but without explanation of the boundary","No sentence in the plan explains why git-object recovery is necessary (e.g., 'needed because the compacted store has no addressable per-field edit history; rebar show gives only current state')"],"finding":"The plan states no positive rationale for why git-object recovery via `git rev-list --objects --all` + `git cat-file` was chosen over the simpler `rebar show`/`rebar list` CLI for building the outcome corpus. The plan says only 'method in report §5,' which is a cross-reference, not a rationale. The absence of a stated rationale means an implementer cannot evaluate whether a simpler approach (e.g., `rebar list --status=closed` for enumeration + `rebar show` for current-state fields) would suffice for any part of the corpus, or whether the git-object path is strictly required throughout.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f01bf2fbd8b6da2a5","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 1 (Mine the outcome corpus); Scope — `harnesses/mine_outcome_corpus.py`","norm_id":"n53b970a1674dad43","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:absence-refuted","scenarios":["Implementer uses rebar show for all fields, missing the per-event edit history needed for post_claim_edit_class; or over-engineers the git path for fields that rebar show already provides","Future maintainer cannot tell which fields require git-object recovery and which can use rebar show, making the script harder to validate and maintain"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add to Step 1: 'Git-object recovery is required because the compacted `.tickets-tracker/` stores only the current reducer-derived state; the rebar CLI (`rebar show`) exposes no per-event description-diff history. Recovering the edit timeline between claim and close requires traversing the git commit graph and diffing description blobs directly.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.3333,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"no","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"na","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E2"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The 'panel' responsible for double-labeling and adjudication is never identified; an executor cannot recruit labelers or begin the kappa step without knowing who constitutes the second (and any additional) rater(s).","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f07305e3f5e72a600","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section ('panel-adjudicated') and AC4 ('>=50-finding double-labeled subset reaches kappa >= 0.7')","norm_id":"na1ceced49620c8bc","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:absence-refuted","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a sentence such as: 'Panel: two human raters — the plan-review author and one independent reviewer (e.g. a second team member or the repo owner); the >=50-finding subset is assigned to both before either sees the other's labels.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"no","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"na","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The mechanism for producing the kappa double-labeled subset is entirely absent from the plan body — the What and Scope sections describe only single-pass panel adjudication, but AC #4 requires an independent second-rater labeling of >=50 findings; the plan provides no work step, rater identification, sampling protocol, or script for this.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"ff88e902f72348dc4","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC #4; What section ('panel-adjudicated TP/FP'); Scope section","norm_id":"n802aa7a2d6a94e37","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:absence-refuted","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"no","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"na","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The kappa calculation protocol in AC#4 lacks a co-located decision rule: who the second rater is (human, LLM, or both), how the >=50-finding double-labeled subset is selected (random, stratified, adversarial), and which kappa formula (Cohen's, Fleiss's, weighted) is to be used are all unspecified.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fa1acb9fa51598b3c","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"AC#4 — 'inter-rater reliability on a >=50-finding double-labeled subset reaches kappa >= 0.7, recorded in the README'","norm_id":"n9fecf3887d9188b0","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:absence-refuted","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"no","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"na","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"AC #4 requires a >=50-finding double-labeled subset and a kappa >= 0.7 calculation, but the 'What' and 'Scope' sections describe no work step to produce this double-labeled subset — no mention of a second rater, labeling protocol, or tool — making AC #4 an orphan criterion with no corresponding described deliverable.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f71e42c0cb8f7ad70","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC #4; What section (panel-adjudicated description)","norm_id":"n9e346b5623bea4c9","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:absence-refuted","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the 'What' section, after 'panel-adjudicated TP/FP', add: 'A randomly stratified subset of >=50 findings is independently labeled by two raters (e.g. primary author + one named reviewer); Cohen's kappa is computed via a committed script (e.g. docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/kappa.py) and recorded in the README.' Mirror this in Scope as a deliverable.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"no","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"na","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The git-mining mechanism (git rev-list --objects --all + cat-file) has no pre-flight completeness probe, so a gc'd or pruned repo silently produces an incomplete outcome corpus that is then committed as 'frozen' ground truth — the re-verification step in AC #2 then passes against wrong labels.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fa069593f0f56d44d","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'Re-derive the §5 event history from git objects across all refs of the tickets branch (git rev-list --objects --all + cat-file; the on-disk .tickets-tracker/ is compacted)'","norm_id":"n49518e7d8689b0bf","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:absence-refuted","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the Scope / mining script design, add an explicit 'object availability check' step: run `git rev-list --count tickets` and `git cat-file --batch-check` on a sampled set of known ticket-edit commits; if any are missing, halt with an actionable error ('gc may have pruned objects; run git fetch --unshallow or restore from the ephemeral artifacts') rather than producing an incomplete corpus.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5714,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"no","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The 'post-claim-edit class' column required in the outcome corpus (AC#1) is an enum whose value vocabulary is never defined anywhere in the plan or referenced artifacts. An executor producing the corpus has no closed set of valid class labels to use.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f6a014336d198aabf","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"AC#1 — 'post-claim-edit class' column; What section — 'labeled with post-claim-edit class'","norm_id":"nc4d4d72c4324da27","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:absence-refuted","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a 'Schema' subsection to the What or Scope section listing the exact allowed values for post-claim-edit class, e.g.: `post_claim_edit_class ∈ {none, cosmetic, functional, structural, revert}` with a one-sentence definition of each.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"no","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"na","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] State the file-system path pattern (or `rebar` CLI subcommand) used to enumerate REVIEW_RESULT sidecars in Step 3 and in the Scope/README regeneration-command description.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E2"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":"novelty","evidence":["'a stratified sample of plan-review findings drawn from the persisted REVIEW_RESULT sidecars'","No path, glob, or access command is given for REVIEW_RESULT sidecars anywhere in the plan or Scope section."],"finding":"The location and access method for REVIEW_RESULT sidecars is never stated in the plan. Step 3 says the adjudication corpus is 'drawn from the persisted REVIEW_RESULT sidecars' but gives no path pattern, directory, or access command. An executor who has not previously worked in this store cannot locate the source population without external investigation.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f4a5627db39d908dc","impact":0.536,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 3 — 'Build the finding-adjudication corpus'","norm_id":"n7c1b4f0b31199435","priority":0.268,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["An executor runs the sampling script and cannot determine where to read REVIEW_RESULT sidecars, requiring a clarifying question or trial-and-error."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"Add a concrete glob or command such as `find docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/ -name 'REVIEW_RESULT*.jsonl'` (or the actual path) to Step 3 and to the README regeneration instructions.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.75,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Commit or cite a verifiable source for the '~527 reviewed tickets' count (e.g. a `rebar list --status=closed | wc -l` snapshot), explain the 505 vs 527 discrepancy (total closed vs reviewed-subset?), and set the pre-flight floor relative to the documented denominator.","cohort":["E4"],"criteria":["E4"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":"novelty","evidence":["Plan text: 'one row per reviewed ticket (~527 reviewed tickets in this store)'","Plan text: 'recovered reviewed-ticket count falls below a floor of 500 (expected ~527)'","§5 published figure is '16/505 = 3.2%' implying 505 reviewed tickets, not 527","No committed query result, rebar list output, or count derivation is findable in the repo","ABSENCE: no file in docs/experiments/ establishes a '527' reviewed-ticket count"],"finding":"The plan asserts '~527 reviewed tickets in this store' as a concrete empirical count that backs the pre-flight floor of 500. This count is stated as a present fact but no source document, query result, or `rebar list` output is committed to the repo to verify it, and the discrepancy with the §5 figure of 505 is unexplained — making both the floor (500) and the expected count (~527) unverifiable assertions.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fb0216183d19fb5b9","impact":0.264,"is_primary":null,"location":"What §1 (Mine the outcome corpus): '~527 reviewed tickets in this store'; Pre-flight probe: 'floor of 500 (expected ~527)'","norm_id":"nc25588bc1234ec57","priority":0.2347,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["The pre-flight probe uses floor=500 which is calibrated to a claimed ~527 count; if the actual count is 480 (due to gc or different counting logic), the floor silently passes when it should halt.","The 505 vs 527 discrepancy (22 tickets) is never explained — it could mean the floor is set relative to the wrong population denominator."],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Add a comment in mine_outcome_corpus.py explaining: TOTAL_CLOSED≈527, REVIEWED_SUBSET (had_persisted_review=True)≈505, floor=480 (90% of reviewed subset) — making the floor derivation explicit and the two counts reconciled.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.8889,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"low","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add `had_persisted_review` to AC1's list of required fields verified by the proving command (e.g. extend the jq/python check to also assert this field is present on every row).","cohort":["COH","E1","T5d"],"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":"novelty","evidence":["Step 1 schema: `{ticket_id, ticket_type, level, post_claim_edit_class, reopen_count (int), force_close (bool), completion_verifier_fail_count (int), review_round_count (int), had_persisted_review (bool)}`","AC1 required fields list: 'carrying `post_claim_edit_class`, `reopen_count`, `force_close`, `completion_verifier_fail_count`, and `review_round_count`' — `had_persisted_review` absent","Step 3 draws from 'persisted REVIEW_RESULT sidecars' implying `had_persisted_review` filters the population"],"finding":"The `had_persisted_review` field is defined in the outcome-corpus schema (Step 1) and is load-bearing for Step 3 (finding-adjudication corpus is drawn from \"the persisted REVIEW_RESULT sidecars\"), but AC1's list of required fields omits it — an AC that doesn't check this field cannot confirm the corpus is complete.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f08553e2341f69054","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 1 (schema definition) vs AC1 proving command","norm_id":"n952b0e91ca8f4d4e","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["An implementer passes AC1 but omits `had_persisted_review` from the corpus; Step 3's stratification silently breaks because the linking field is absent."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In AC1, extend the proving command to `python -c \"import json,sys; rows=list(map(json.loads,open('runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl'))); assert all('had_persisted_review' in r for r in rows)\"` or equivalent jq, and add `had_persisted_review` to the enumerated field list.","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Confirm whether `harnesses/kappa.py` can import and delegate to `src/rebar/llm/evals/eval.py::cohens_kappa` (stdlib-only, no side-effects) instead of re-implementing the algorithm, to avoid a third divergent copy.","cohort":["A1"],"criteria":["A1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":"novelty","evidence":["`src/rebar/llm/evals/eval.py` lines 343–359: `def cohens_kappa(rater_a: list, rater_b: list) -> float` — full, tested, stdlib-only implementation","`scripts/calibrate_completion_floor.py` lines 46–55: `def _kappa(pairs)` — second standalone implementation","Plan Scope: '`harnesses/kappa.py` (new)' — proposes a third implementation","`eval.py` header: 'stdlib-only and offline-testable; only the actual *run* … is network-bound' — the existing function is importable without side-effects"],"finding":"The proposed `harnesses/kappa.py` re-implements Cohen's kappa from scratch when `src/rebar/llm/evals/eval.py` already exports a tested, stdlib-only `cohens_kappa()` function (and `scripts/calibrate_completion_floor.py` has a second inline `_kappa()`), making kappa.py a third independent implementation of the same algorithm.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fdb880e51d6b226dd","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Step 4 / Scope: `harnesses/kappa.py` (new); AC#4 proving command","norm_id":"n6d9f2f216cc25050","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Three independent kappa implementations drift apart: `eval.py`'s handles degenerate all-same-label cases (pe==1.0) with special-casing; a freshly written kappa.py may not, producing different results on edge cases in the adjudication corpus.","A future kappa bug fix in `eval.py` is not propagated to the standalone harness script, leaving the corpus's recorded kappa value computed by a divergent formula."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In kappa.py, do `import sys, pathlib; sys.path.insert(0, str(pathlib.Path(__file__).parents[4] / 'src')); from rebar.llm.evals.eval import cohens_kappa` and call it directly, or copy the single function with a comment crediting the source and a TODO to consolidate.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.875,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","l